y estimation in GNN-based molecular force fields is critical for practical applications, especially when dealing with out-of-distribution data. The Localized Neural Kernel (LNK) method shows promise but requires further refinement and validation.\n\n**5q Research Proposal**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the problem with existing uncertainty estimation methods in GNN-based molecular force fields, and how can we improve them to provide reliable uncertainty estimates for out-of-distribution data?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem is crucial for advancing molecular dynamics simulations and other applications that rely on accurate molecular force predictions. Reliable uncertainty estimation can prevent errors in simulations and improve the robustness of models in practical scenarios.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nImproving uncertainty estimation in GNNs is challenging due to the complexity of molecular data and the need to balance predictive performance with uncertainty estimation. Existing methods often fail to meet both criteria simultaneously, and naive approaches may not capture the nuances of molecular interactions.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious UE methods have not fully satisfied the physical-informed and application-focused desiderata for molecular force fields. The LNK method addresses some of these gaps but requires further refinement to ensure reliable performance across a wide range of datasets.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves refining and extending the LNK method to improve its uncertainty estimation capabilities. The method will be evaluated on various molecular datasets using metrics such as AUC-ROC scores to compare its performance against existing UE methods. Expected outcomes include a more reliable UE method that can handle OOD data effectively.\n\nThis summary 