g UE methods to handle OOD data will significantly improve the reliability of molecular force fields, making them more robust for practical applications. By integrating these methods with Bayesian Optimization, we can accelerate the discovery of novel materials with optimal properties, which is essential for advancing renewable energy technologies. This research will not only push the boundaries of computational chemistry but also contribute to the broader field of materials science by providing more efficient and accurate tools for material discovery.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in developing a UE method that can reliably estimate uncertainty with a single forward pass without compromising predictive performance. Existing methods often fail to meet both physical-informed and application-focused criteria, and naive approaches may not address the complexities of OOD data. Integrating UE with Bayesian Optimization adds another layer of complexity, as it requires balancing exploration and exploitation in the search for optimal material compositions.\n\n**Answer**:\nDeveloping a UE method that can handle OOD data while maintaining predictive performance is a significant challenge. Existing methods often struggle to meet both physical-informed and application-focused criteria, and naive approaches may not adequately address the complexities of OOD data. Integrating UE with Bayesian Optimization further complicates the problem, as it requires balancing exploration and exploitation to efficiently discover optimal material compositions. These challenges necessitate a novel approach that can address these issues effectively.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious UE methods, such as dropout-based and evidential-based approaches, do not fully satisfy the physical-informed and application-focused desiderata. The integration of UE with Bayesian Optimization for material discovery adds another layer of complexity that has 