olecular dynamics simulations, and metrics, such as AUC-ROC scores, to demonstrate its effectiveness in uncertainty estimation and material discovery. Expected outcomes include improved reliability of molecular force fields, more accurate predictions, and enhanced efficiency in material discovery processes.\n\n### Conclusion\nThe refined research proposal clearly outlines the problem, its importance, the challenges involved, and the proposed solution. This structured approach ensures that the research is well-aligned with the goals of enhancing uncertainty estimation in molecular force fields and integrating it with Bayesian Optimization for efficient material discovery.\n"}, {'agent2': "Result from the model:To refine the research proposal and ensure it is clear, comprehensive, and actionable, I will follow the outlined steps. Here is the detailed plan and execution:\n\n### Step 1: Refine the Research Proposal\n\n#### Clarity and Precision\n- **Question 1:** What is the problem?\n  - **Refined:** How can we develop a reliable uncertainty estimation method for GNN-based molecular force fields that performs well on both in-distribution and out-of-distribution data?\n- **Question 2:** Why is it interesting and important?\n  - **Refined:** Solving this problem is crucial for improving the reliability of GNN-based molecular force fields in practical applications. Reliable uncertainty estimation can help detect unforeseen events and improve the robustness of molecular dynamics simulations. This research will advance the field of computational chemistry and materials science by providing a more accurate and reliable tool for predicting molecular behavior.\n- **Question 3:** Why is it hard?\n  - **Refined:** Developing a reliable uncertainty estimation method for GNN-based molecular force fields is challenging due to the complex nature of molecular systems and the difficulty in capturing out-of-distribution scenarios. Existing methods often fail to generalize well to OOD data, and incorporating uncertainty estimation into GNNs can be technically complex.\n- **Question 4:** Why hasn't it been solved before?\n  - **Refined:** Previous research has focused on improving the predictive performance of GNNs but has not adequately addressed the challenge of reliable uncertainty estimation on OOD data. The complexity of molecular systems and the need for a method that satisfies both physical-informed and application-focused desiderata have hindered progress in this area.\n- **Question 5:** What are the key components of my approach and results?\n  - **Refined:** The proposed approach involves developing a Gaussian Process (GP)-based extension to existing GNN-based force fields, called Localized Neural Kernel (LNK). This method will be trained on a diverse dataset of molecular structures and will be evaluated on both in-distribution and out-of-distribution data. The expected outcomes include improved uncertainty estimation and enhanced robustness of molecular force fields, as demonstrated by lower errors in terms of AUC-ROC score compared to existing methods.\n\n#### Literature Context\n- **Introduction:** Incorporate the context from the Introduction to support the research questions and the proposed approach.\n  - **Refined:** The use of graph neural networks (GNNs) for predicting molecular forces and energies has shown promise in accelerating molecular dynamics simulations. However, these models often struggle with out-of-distribution (OOD) data, leading to unreliable predictions. There is a need for a robust uncertainty estimation method that can reliably estimate uncertainty on OOD data without compromising predictive performance. Existing methods, such as dropout-based and evidential-based UE, have been applied to GNNs for molecular force fields but have achieved good performance on in-distribution data but fail to reliably estimate uncertainty on OOD data.\n\n#### Feasibility\n- **Assessment:** Assess the feasibility of the proposed methodology, including the availability of datasets, computational resources, and time constraints.\n  - **Refined:** The feasibility of the proposed methodology is supported by the availability of diverse molecular datasets, such as QM9 and MD17, which can be used for training and evaluation. Computational resources, including GPUs and cloud-based computing platforms, are available for training the models. The time constraints are manageable, with a phased approach that includes literature review, data collection, model development, evaluation, and writing.\n\n### Step 2: Develop a Detailed Methodology\n\n#### Method\n- **Description:** Provide a detailed description of the Localized Neural Kernel (LNK) method, including the architecture, training process, and any modifications to existing GNNs.\n  - **Refined:** The Localized Neural Kernel (LNK) method is a Gaussian Process (GP)-based extension to existing GNN-based force fields. The architecture consists of a GNN layer that processes molecular graphs and a GP layer that estimates uncertainty. The training process involves optimizing the GNN parameters and the GP hyperparameters using a combination of supervised and unsupervised learning techniques. Modifications to existing GNNs include the integration of a GP layer and the use of localized kernels to capture the uncertainty in molecular structures.\n\n#### Dataset\n- **Specification:** Specify the datasets to be used for training and evaluation, including any preprocessing steps.\n  - **Refined:** The datasets to be used for training and evaluation include QM9 and MD17, which contain molecular structures and their corresponding forces and energies. Preprocessing steps include data normalization, feature extraction, and graph construction.\n\n#### Metrics\n- **Definition:** Define the metrics for evaluating the performance of the LNK method, such as AUC-ROC score, mean squared error, and other relevant metrics.\n  - **Refined:** The metrics for evaluating the performance of the LNK method include AUC-ROC score for uncertainty estimation, mean squared error for predictive performance, and other relevant metrics such as root mean squared error (RMSE) and mean absolute error (MAE).\n\n### Step 3: Prepare a Preliminary Timeline\n\n#### Phases\n- **Breakdown:** Break down the research into phases, such as literature review, data collection, model development, evaluation, and writing.\n  - **Refined:** The research will be broken down into the following phases:\n    1. Literature Review (1 month)\n    2. Data Collection and Preprocessing (2 months)\n    3. Model Development (3 months)\n    4. Evaluation (2 months)\n    5. Writing (2 months)\n\n#### Milestones\n- **Setting:** Set specific milestones for each phase to ensure progress and track completion.\n  - **Refined:** The milestones for each phase are as follows:\n    1. Literature Review: Completion of a comprehensive literature review and identification of key research gaps (1 month)\n    2. Data Collection and Preprocessing: Collection and preprocessing of datasets (2 months)\n    3. Model Development: Development and training of the LNK method (3 months)\n    4. Evaluation: Evaluation of the LNK method on in-distribution and out-of-distribution data (2 months)\n    5. Writing: Writing and submission of the research paper (2 months)\n\n### Step 4: Seek Feedback\n\n#### Colleagues\n- **Sharing:** Share the refined research proposal with colleagues or mentors for feedback.\n  - **Refined:** The refined research proposal will be shared with colleagues and mentors for feedback to ensure clarity, feasibility, and relevance.\n\n#### Pilot Studies\n- **Conducting:** Consider conducting a small pilot study to validate the methodology and gather preliminary results.\n  - **Refined:** A small pilot study will be conducted to validate the methodology and gather preliminary results, which will be used to refine the research proposal further.\n\n### Step 5: Write a Draft Paper\n\n#### Introduction\n- **Summarization:** Summarize the problem, existing approaches, and the proposed solution.\n  - **Refined:** The introduction will summarize the problem of unreliable uncertainty estimation in GNN-based molecular force fields, existing approaches, and the proposed solution, which is the Localized Neural Kernel (LNK) method.\n\n#### Methodology\n- **Detailing:** Detail the proposed method, datasets, and evaluation metrics.\n  - **Refined:** The methodology section will detail the proposed Localized Neural Kernel (LNK) method, including the architecture, training process, and modifications to existing GNNs. The datasets and evaluation metrics will also be detailed.\n\n#### Results\n- **Outlining:** Outline the expected results and how they will be presented.\n  - **Refined:** The results section will outline the expected outcomes, including improved uncertainty estimation and enhanced robustness of molecular force fields, as demonstrated by lower errors in terms of AUC-ROC score compared to existing methods. The results will be presented using tables, figures, and statistical analysis.\n\n#### Conclusion\n- **Discussing:** Discuss the implications of the research and future work.\n  - **Refined:** The conclusion will discuss the implications of the research, including the potential impact on the field of computational chemistry and materials science. Future work will also be discussed, including the extension of the LNK method to other molecular systems and the integration of additional uncertainty estimation techniques.\n\nBy following these steps, the research proposal will be well-structured, feasible, and ready for further development.\n"}, {'agent3': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Successfully completed session e89eb395-4012-4b8e-8303-aae57ec518b7", "full_chat_history": "In Session e89eb395-4012-4b8e-8303-aae57ec518b7 \\nFrom agent3 to agent4: I have drafted a detailed research proposal based on the refi